What happens when you initialize a repository? Why do you need to do it?
	Git creates its badass folder on the directiory that was initialized the repository. I need to do it so I can make commits.

How is the staging area different from the working directory and the repository? What value do you think it offers?
	Staging area is the place you hold the files you want to make part of one commit. Once the commit is made, than it goes to the repository. Working directory is where your file are befour you add them to the staging area.

How can you use the staging area to make sure you have one commit per logical change?
	The staging area is the bubble that contains the files that will make part of a single commit. This way, you can add only the files that represent a single logical change.

What are some situations when branches would be helpful in keeping your history organized? How would branches help?
	Wnhen you want to try out something that you're not sure gonna make part of the main version of you project. So, when you create a new branch, you're adding another "commit line" paralel to the master one.

